                <head>177. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>Following the Heads of Government meeting at 10 a.m. (see <ref target="#d176"
                        >Document 176</ref>), President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName> and Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_MH1"
                        >Macmillan</persName> visited the British Embassy, Barnes la Coquette, where
                    the President had lived when he was the Supreme Allied Commander for Europe, and
                    finally, about 1 p.m., the President returned to the U.S. Embassy. According to
                        <persName corresp="#p_BCE1">Bohlen</persName>, he and some other members of
                    the U.S. Delegation then had dinner with the President, after which they
                    discussed the prospects of the conference. For <persName corresp="#p_BCE1"
                        >Bohlen</persName>’s account of this discussion, see <persName
                        corresp="#p_BCE1">Bohlen</persName>, <hi rend="italic">Witness to
                        History</hi>, pages 468–469. No other record of this discussion has been
                    found although the dinner (called a lunch) is mentioned in <persName
                        corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName>, <hi rend="italic">Strictly
                        Personal</hi>, page 277.</p>
            </div>
